            "new_string": "## Evaluation algorithms\n\nEach stage uses a different technique to catch bad answers. Here's what's under the hood.\n\n### LLM self-evaluation (Confidence, Verification)\n\nStructured prompting with JSON schema constraints. The LLM scores its own confidence and relevance on a 0.0-1.0 scale, then independently re-derives the answer without seeing the original. Scores are clamped to [0.0, 1.0]. If the independent re-derivation disagrees, the answer is dropped.\n\n### Adversarial dialectic (Adversarial)\n\nTwo-step argue-then-defend protocol. Step 1: the LLM generates the strongest possible counter-argument against the result. Step 2: a separate LLM call attempts to defend the original answer against that counter-argument. If the defense fails, the answer is dropped. This catches answers that sound plausible but can't withstand scrutiny.\n\n### Self-consistency sampling (Self-Consistency)\n\nImplementation of [Wang et al. 2022](https://arxiv.org/abs/2203.11171). The LLM independently solves the same task N times (default 3), producing N candidate answers in parallel. Each candidate is then compared to the agent's original answer via a binary agreement check (\"do these agree on the core conclusion?\"). The agreement rate (agree_count / N) is blended with existing confidence by taking the minimum. Low agreement = the answer is likely wrong.\n\n### Cosine similarity on sentence embeddings (Semantic Similarity)\n\nUses [all-MiniLM-L6-v2](https://huggingface.co/sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2) (80MB) to encode the task and the answer into 384-dimensional vectors, then computes cosine similarity: `dot(a, b) / (||a|| * ||b||)`. Catches off-topic or irrelevant answers without any LLM call. Falls back to an LLM-based relevance rating if `sentence-transformers` is not installed.\n\n### Natural Language Inference (Entailment)\n\nUses [cross-encoder/nli-deberta-v3-small](https://huggingface.co/cross-encoder/nli-deberta-v3-small) (180MB), a DeBERTa-v3 model fine-tuned on NLI datasets. Classifies the (task_context, answer) pair into three probabilities: entailment, neutral, contradiction. If contradiction > 0.5, the answer is dropped. Confidence is adjusted by an entailment factor: `confidence * (0.5 + 0.5 * max(0, entailment - contradiction))`. This uses a completely different model architecture, breaking the \"same brain grading itself\" problem. Falls back to LLM-based classification if `transformers`/`torch` are not installed.\n\n### Token log-probability calibration (Logprob)\n\nAsks the LLM to restate the answer in its own words and reads per-token log probabilities from the API response (OpenAI only — Anthropic doesn't expose logprobs). Converts to confidence via `exp(mean_logprob)`: a mean logprob of 0 maps to 1.0 (certain), -3 maps to ~0.05 (uncertain). This is a real signal from the model's internals, not self-reported confidence. The logprob confidence is blended with existing confidence by averaging. Falls back to keeping existing confidence if logprobs are unavailable.\n\n### Prompt injection mitigation\n\nAll user-controlled content (`task_context`, `result`, `justification`, `counter_argument`) is wrapped in semantic XML tags and escaped before interpolation into prompts. Tag sequences appearing within user content are HTML-entity-escaped to prevent delimiter breakout. A boundary instruction tells the evaluation LLM to treat tagged sections as data only, not as instructions.\n\n## Running tests",
